I added **paths** in tsconfig.app.json

```
{
  "compileOnSave": false,
  "compilerOptions": {
  ...
    "paths": {
      "exceljs": [
        "node_modules/exceljs/dist/exceljs.js"
      ]
    }
  },
  "angularCompilerOptions": {
    "fullTemplateTypeCheck": true,
    "strictInjectionParameters": true
  }
}
```

Update: per stackoverflow 
https://stackoverflow.com/questions/43017736/integrating-aws-sdk-to-angular2-gives-cannot-find-module-stream 
people were adding this to src/tsconfig.json. For some reason I had no tsconfig.json file under the src, I only had it in the root. I created one in the src file, and implemented the following:

`{
  "extends": "./tsconfig.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "types": [
      "node"
    ]
  }
}`

And the error went away. Hope that helps someone else.

--original--
Sadly none of the suggested fixes worked for me, either.

>  "paths": {
>       "exceljs": [
>         "node_modules/exceljs/dist/exceljs.js"
>       ]
>     }

I'm using now Angular 11.xx.x and using this configuration doesn't work for me, but I modify it like this, and **now it's working**...
```

{
  "extends": "./tsconfig.json",
  "compilerOptions": {
    "outDir": "./out-tsc/app",
    "paths": {
      "exceljs": [
        "node_modules/exceljs/dist"
      ]
    }
  },
  "files": [
    "src/main.ts",
    "src/polyfills.ts"
  ],
  "include": [
    "src/**/*.d.ts"
   #]
}

```

>  I added paths in **tsconfig.json** not **tsconfig.app.json**  and it worked
i.e.
```
{
  "compileOnSave": false,
  "compilerOptions": {
    "baseUrl": "./",
    "outDir": "./dist/out-tsc",
    "sourceMap": true,
    "declaration": false,
    "paths": {
      "exceljs": [
        "node_modules/exceljs/dist/exceljs.js"
      ]
    }
  },
  "angularCompilerOptions": {
    "enableI18nLegacyMessageIdFormat": false,
    "enableIvy": true
  }
}
```
